Control Flow â€“ Branching

Branching allows a program to make decisions and execute different blocks of code depending on conditions.

The most common form of branching in Python uses the if/elif/else structure:

if condition:
    # execute this block
elif another_condition:
    # execute this block
else:
    # execute this default block

Conditions are typically boolean expressions, using comparison operators such as ==, !=, >, <, >=, and <=.

Example:
x = 10
if x > 5:
    print("x is greater than 5")
elif x == 5:
    print("x is equal to 5")
else:
    print("x is less than 5")
